  "prompt": "Why didn't Balram (brother of Krishna) participate in the Mahabharat War?",
  "response": "Balram, the elder brother of Lord Krishna, did not participate in the Mahabharat War for several reasons:\n\n1. **Neutrality**: Balram preferred to remain neutral in the conflict. He was a teacher to both Duryodhana and Bhima in the art of mace fighting (Gada Yuddha), and both sides respected him greatly. He did not want to take sides in the war, which he viewed as a devastating family feud.\n\n2. **Pilgrimage**: During the time of the Mahabharat War, Balram chose to go on a pilgrimage. This was another way for him to distance himself from the conflict and avoid taking part in the warfare.\n\n3. **Different Perspective**: Balram had a different perspective on the war compared to Krishna. While Krishna played a crucial role in the war, guiding the Pandavas and serving as Arjuna's charioteer, Balram felt that the war was unnecessary and could have been avoided. This difference in viewpoint contributed to his decision to stay away.\n\nThese factors combined led to Balram's absence from the Mahabharat War, highlighting his desire to remain neutral and his disapproval of the conflict.",
